      <div class="prose">
        <p>Residential HVAC delivers higher profit margins, primarily due to lower materials costs as a percentage of total project value. A $8,000 residential system replacement might cost $3,200 in materials (40%), while a $200,000 commercial project could cost $100,000 in materials (50%).</p>

        <p>Commercial jobs have higher overhead percentages due to bonding requirements, specialized insurance, and longer project timelines. However, the absolute dollar profit on commercial work is still substantially higher. A 15% margin on a $200,000 commercial job nets $30,000 profit, compared to $2,000 profit on a 25% margin residential job worth $8,000.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="operational-differences">Operational Differences</h2>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>The operational requirements for commercial versus residential HVAC are fundamentally different. Understanding these differences is crucial for planning your business transition or specialization.</p>

        <h3>Workforce Requirements</h3>

        <p>Residential HVAC operates with smaller teams. Most jobs require 1-2 technicians working for 4-8 hours. Commercial projects need 3-8 technicians working for weeks or months. A typical residential company runs efficiently with 5-10 technicians, while commercial operations often require 15-50+ technicians to handle multiple concurrent projects.</p>

        <h3>Equipment and Vehicle Investments</h3>

        <p>Residential contractors can operate with standard service vans ($40,000-$60,000 each) and portable tools ($15,000-$25,000 per truck). Commercial operations require specialized equipment: boom lifts ($80,000-$150,000), larger trucks ($100,000-$200,000), and heavy-duty tools ($50,000-$100,000 per crew).</p>

        <h3>Licensing and Insurance</h3>

        <p>Commercial HVAC demands higher licensing requirements in most states. Contractors need master licenses, EPA certifications, and often specialized credentials for specific commercial systems. Insurance costs are 2-3x higher for commercial work, with general liability policies starting at $15,000-$25,000 annually versus $5,000-$8,000 for residential.</p>
      </div>

